==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Kulturkampf
<hw>Kul*tur"kampf`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[G., fr.
<ets>kultur</ets>, <ets>cultur</ets>, culture + <ets>kampf</ets>
fight.]</ety> <fld>(Ger. Hist.)</fld> <def>Lit., culture war; -- a name,
originating with <persfn>Virchow</persfn> (1821 - 1902), given to a
struggle between the Roman Catholic Church and the German government,
chiefly over the latter's efforts to control educational and
ecclesiastical appointments in the interest of the political policy of
centralization. The struggle began with the passage by the Prussian Diet
in May, 1873, of the so-called <col><b>May laws</b></col>, or
<col><b>Falk laws</b></col>, aiming at the regulation of the clergy.
Opposition eventually compelled the government to change its policy, and
from 1880 to 1887 laws virtually nullifying the May laws were
enacted.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

